{"id":"hep-ph/9711449","submitter":null,"authors":"M. Consoli and P. M. Stevenson","title":"lambda Phi^4 Theory From a Particle-Gas Viewpoint","comments":"40 pages, no figures, LaTeX","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"DE-FG05-92ER40717-46","categories":"hep-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We discuss the physics of the 3+1 dimensional lambda Phi^4 quantum field\ntheory in terms of the statistical mechanics of a gas of particles (`atoms')\nthat interact via a -1/r^3-plus-hard-core potential. The hard-core potential,\ndelta^(3)(r), arises from the bare vertex diagram, while the attractive,\nlong-range -1/r^3 potential is due to exchange of a particle pair via the\nt,u-channel \"fish\" diagram. (Higher-order diagrams preserve this form of the\ninterparticle potential.) For sufficiently small atom mass, the lowest-energy\nstate is not the `empty' state with no atoms, but a state with a non-zero\ndensity of spontaneously created atoms, Bose-condensed in the zero-momentum\nmode. This corresponds to the spontaneous-symmetry-breaking phase transition,\nand the `phonon' excitations of the Bose condensate correspond to Higgs\nparticles. The important point is that the phase transition happens while the\natom's physical mass m is still positive: it does not wait until m^2 passes\nthrough zero and becomes negative, contrary to the assumption of a second-order\ntransition, on which renormalization-group-improved perturbation theory is\nbased.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 24 Nov 1997 22:08:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
